      <body>
         <div type="letter">
            <pb n="1" facs="Edgeworth_Bodleian_696_1819_04_07_page01.jpg"/>
            <!--filenames for photos associated with this letter. Example: <pb n="1" facs="image1.jpg image2.jpg image3.jpg"/> -->
            <opener>
               <dateline><!--If there's no date line, omit this element. Record in the order in which it is written on the letter.-->
                  <name type="place" ref="Id_where"/>
                  <date when="1816-08-04"/>August 4, 1816. </dateline>
               <salute>
                  <persName>
                     <!-- Use if letter has a saluation ("Dear Sir," for example). If not, delete this line.-->
                  </persName>
               </salute>
            </opener>
            <p>Dearest mother, <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF3">Fanny</persName> is<lb/>
                better and with the care<lb/>
                which she is certain of <choice><orig>hav<lb/>
                ing</orig><reg>having</reg></choice> in this dear good <choice><orig>fami<lb/>
                ly</orig><reg>family</reg></choice> and under <persName ref="./Personography.xml#HollP1">D<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. Hollands</persName><lb/>
                medical skill &amp; friendly<lb/>
                care she will in a few<lb/>
                days be quite refitted<lb/></p>

             <p>   She has had two blisters<lb/>
                one on her chest one on<lb/>
                her side for that vile pain<lb/>
                in her side. She has taken<lb/>
                saline draughts &amp; pills &amp;<lb/>
                opening medicines &amp; <choice><orig>Anti-<lb/>
                mony</orig><reg>Antimony</reg></choice> - and her pulse<lb/>
                has come down to a weak<lb/>
                state - no fever remains<lb/>
                - but very little pain in her<lb/>
                side - nothing but weak<lb/>
                ness remains - &amp; well she<lb/>
                may be weak having <add>had</add> <choice><orig>no-<lb/>
                thing</orig><reg>nothing</reg></choice> but barley water &amp;<lb/>
                such stuff these 3 days<lb/>

                <pb n="2" facs="Edgeworth_Bodleian_696_1819_04_07_page02.jpg"/> 

                - while fever lasted she c<hi rend="superscript">d</hi>.<lb/>
                have no appetite &amp; <persName ref="./Personography.xml#HollP1">D<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. Holland</persName><lb/>
                and Common sense says<lb/>
                that it was hurtful to press<lb/>
                her to eat till she wished<lb/>
                it - I enclose <persName ref="./Personography.xml#HollP1">D<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. Hollands</persName><lb/>
                note of this morning - he<lb/>
                insists you see on her being<lb/>
                kept from all that can<lb/>
                agitate her. I fairly told him<lb/>
                her mind had been kept<lb/>
                in a harrassing state.<lb/>
                Armed with his medical<lb/>
                orders I shall insist on<lb/>
                no person's seeing her till<lb/>
                <persName ref="./Personography.xml#HollP1">D<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. H</persName> says it is safe.<lb/></p>

            <p>    <persName ref="./Personography.xml#WilsL1">LW</persName> had before she was<lb/>
                ill been promised that<lb/>
               he should meet us at <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BailJ1"><choice><orig>Joan<lb/>
                  na</orig><reg>Joanna</reg></choice> Baillie</persName>'s on Thursday.<lb/></p>

            <p>    That is impossible - I will<lb/>
                dine there &amp; meet him &amp;<lb/>
                <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BeauF1">Francis</persName> and return here<lb/>
                in the eve<hi rend="superscript">g</hi>. - I must dine<lb/>
                lest I sh<hi rend="superscript">d</hi>. mortally offend<lb/>
                the good Baillie's - I must<lb/>
                also dine there on Saturday<lb/>

                <pb n="3" facs="Edgeworth_Bodleian_696_1819_04_07_page03.jpg"/>

                because we <hi rend="underline">had</hi> engaged and<lb/>
                <unclear>loads</unclear> of Baillies &amp; people have<lb/>
                been engaged to meet us.<lb/></p>

            <p>    But depend upon it dear
                mother <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF3">Fanny</persName> <hi rend="underline">shall</hi> not
                go to be stewed &amp; agitated
                into a fever again. She shall
                stay in this delightful
                house &amp; with this dear
                family till she is quite
                stout. Then she shall see
                <persName ref="./Personography.xml#WilsL1">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. L W</persName> once again &amp;
                then I will insist upon
                setting off immediately
                afterwards - To <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Deep-Dene-Dorking_ENK">Deep Dene</placeName>
                I think on the 17<hi rend="superscript">th</hi>. -</p>

            <p>    Whether to cheat or not<lb/>
                to cheat the <persName ref="./Personography.xml#TaddX2"><unclear>Taddys</unclear></persName> for<lb/>
                the 22<hi rend="superscript">d</hi>. 23 &amp; 29<hi rend="superscript">th</hi>. I have<lb/>
                not yet made up my mind<lb/>
                - nor can I till I see how<lb/>
                <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF3">Fanny</persName> is<lb/></p>

             <p>   We must <add>I think</add> spend 2 or 3 days<lb/>
                with <persName ref="./Personography.xml#WhitE1">Lady E W</persName> when <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF3">Fanny</persName>s<lb/>
                final answer has been<lb/>
                given - This was her request<lb/>
                &amp; my promise<lb/>
                172

                <pb n="4" facs="Edgeworth_Bodleian_696_1819_04_07_page04.jpg"/>

                I will write again tomorrow<lb/></p>

             <p>   I know what I write<lb/>
                to day is a little in <choice><orig>contra<lb/>
                diction</orig><reg>contradiction</reg></choice> to what I wrote<lb/>
                to you yesterday of our<lb/>
                intentions but I cannot<lb/>
                help it - I can only <del>decide</del> <add>judge</add><lb/>
                from day to day according<lb/>
                as circumstances occur<lb/>
                &amp; as <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF3">Fanny</persName>s health decides<lb/></p>

            <p>    I enclose a sugar plum<lb/>
                for you my dearest friend<lb/>
                - <persName ref="./Personography.xml#LawsW1">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. <unclear>West Lawson's</unclear></persName> letter about<lb/>
                your dear boy who has crept<lb/>
                (like cupid into the armor)<lb/>
                into <persName ref="./Personography.xml#CarrF1">M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi>. Carrs</persName> heart -<lb/></p>
            <p>
                I enclose <persName ref="./Personography.xml#HopeX">M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi>. Hopes</persName> letter<lb/>
                to shew she is not tired<lb/>
               of us-</p>

            <p>    <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BeauF1">Capt<hi rend="superscript">n</hi>. Beaufort</persName> sent me yesterday<lb/>
                a letter of <persName ref="./Personography.xml#NewiX1">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. Newingtons</persName> giving<lb/>
                better hopes than I have yet seen<lb/>
                of <persName ref="./Personography.xml#XxxxW1">W</persName> - <persName ref="./Personography.xml#NewiX1">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. Newingtons</persName> account<lb/>
                <unclear>14th. </unclear> <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BeauF1">Francis</persName> also sent me<lb/>
                saying he must pay it immediately<lb/>
                - I sent a draft to bearer on <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Fleet-Street-37_ENK">Hoare</placeName><lb/>
                for the amount - desiring <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BeauF1">Francis</persName><lb/>
                to tear it if he had any other money<lb/>
                lodged to answer the demand<lb/>
                - I presume he has not as he<lb/>

                <pb n="5" facs="Edgeworth_Bodleian_696_1819_04_07_page05.jpg"/> 

                saw me yesterday evening<lb/>
                and did not return my<lb/>
                draft or say any thing about<lb/>
                it - and my head was so full<lb/>
                of <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF3">Fanny</persName> I could not <choice><orig>recol-<lb/>
                lect</orig><reg>recollect</reg></choice> to ask him<lb/></p>

             <p>   Most fortunately I had the<lb/>
                money at <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Fleet-Street-37_ENK">Hoares</placeName>- But I<lb/>
                was frightened this morn<hi rend="superscript">g</hi>.<lb/>
                when on balancing my<lb/>
                account I found I had<lb/>
                drawn within £5-<lb/></p>

           <p>     <del>Lovells</del> The draft for<lb/>
                £221 Annuity you know<lb/>
                was at 21 days <del>sight</del> I<lb/>
                have had it presented<lb/>
                and in 18 days now<lb/>
                it will be due &amp; paid<lb/>
                and meantime time I have<lb/>
                £90 in my hands in notes<lb/></p>

            <p>    I fear to be too late<lb/>
                173<!-- Begin transcibing the body of the letter here. -->
            </p>
            </p>
